            <div class="section-label">Background</div>
            <h2>About <span class="accent">This Resource</span></h2>
        </div>
        <div class="prose">
            <p>SLP/IO is a <strong>Harmonic Systems</strong> project — built by a speech-language pathologist and software developer who has spent years working at the intersection of clinical practice, voice science, and technology.</p>

            <p>Harmonic Systems is a small, independent studio exploring the intersection of clinical practice and software — including iOS apps, web tools, and audio projects informed by real SLP work.</p>

            <p>SLP/IO exists because clinicians are already using language models informally, often without a framework for doing so safely or effectively. The goal is not to promote AI adoption. It's to define what responsible use looks like in a field where language carries legal and clinical weight.</p>

            <p>These tools are entering clinical workflows whether we're ready or not. The question is not whether to use them, but how to use them in a way that strengthens — not weakens — clinical thinking.</p>

            <blockquote>
                <strong>About the author:</strong> David Nyman, MS CCC-SLP, is a school-based speech-language pathologist in the Hudson Valley region of New York. He splits his time between clinical work and building software tools informed by that practice. SLP/IO is his attempt to bridge the gap between what clinicians need and what the technology conversation currently offers.
            </blockquote>

